ECLOGUE VI.

PREFACE.

Alfenus Varus, to whom this poem is addressed‚ was consul suffectus, 39 B.C., and succeeded Pollio as governor of Cisalpine Gaul. Vergil seems to have intended to celebrate Varus' warlike deeds, a task which we may suppose he gave up partly because he felt it beyond him, and partly because he considered it would be indiscreet to write on contemporary wars. Silenus’ song in2 this Eclogue shows how strongly Vergil was influenced by Lucretius, whose poem De Rerum· Natam had recently been published.
